\emph{\textbf{Short-Answer Problems.} A correct answer in the box gives
full marks. For partial marks work needs to be shown.}

\emph{Note: If a limit does not exist, indicate whether it approaches
$+\infty$ or $-\infty$.}

Find the limit

\begin{align*}\displaystyle A= \lim_{x \to \infty}\frac{2x^4-3x^3+5}{2x^3-5x^4}\end{align*}

sols:
\begin{align*}\displaystyle A= \lim_{x \to \infty}\frac{2x^4-3x^3+5}{2x^3-5x^4}\end{align*}

To evaluate this limit, first we divide both the numerator and
denominator by the largest power of $x$ that appears in this fraction.
In this case, $x^{4}$ is the largest power.

\begin{align*}\displaystyle A= \lim_{x \to \infty}\frac{2-3/x+5/x^{4}}{2/x-5}.\end{align*}

Now all that's left to finish the problem, is calculating the limits
separately:

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle A &= \lim_{x \to \infty}\frac{2-3/x+5/x^{4}}{2/x-5} \\
&= \frac{\lim_{x \to \infty} 2-3/x+5/x^{4}}{\lim_{x \to \infty} 2/x-5}
&= \frac{2}{-5}\end{align*}

Therefore,

\begin{align*}\displaystyle {\color{blue}A =-\frac{2}{5}}.\end{align*}
